Source: The Associated Press, 27 Nov 2000 3:01 p.m. EST [edited
<http://www.nandotimes.com/healthscience/story/0,1080,500284068-500447506-502>

Ebola Hemorrhagic Fever Death Reported in Southwestern Uganda
--------------------------------------------------------------
KAMPALA: On Mon 27 Nov 2000, Ugandan officials recorded another death from
Ebola virus infection in the southwest of the country. Meanwhile, 14
others died from the highly contagious virus in the north. The Ebola
outbreak - Uganda's first - originated in the town of Gulu, 225 miles north
of Kampala, with the first of hundreds of victims showing symptoms in
September. A total of 17 new cases was reported on Monday, said Francis
Omaswa, Director General Of Health Services. In all, 145 people have now
died of the disease. Authorities had hoped to keep the disease from
spreading beyond Gulu. However, since 12 Nov 2000, 4 people have died in
the town of Masindi, southwest of Gulu, including one death on Saturday,
said Dr. Imaan Mutyaba, a medical supervisor. 4 others have died of Ebola
in the town of Mbarara.
The fever caused by the Ebola virus is transmitted through body
fluids. The disease can cause severe hemorrhagic fever and is often
fatal. While there is no cure, patients aggressively treated for
dehydration have a good chance of survival.
